f the production and reception of poetry, and alters our understanding of the way poetry participated in social, literary and political life.The volume takes account of the expansion and changes to the canon of women’s poetry and emerging research on key aspects of literary production and reception. It builds on and responds to both recent critical emphasis on literary form and on archival scholarship in women’s writing, understanding the two emphases to be mutually informative. This book explores the way women understood the poem, examines how the poem was shared, circulated and rewritten, and traces its path through wider social relations. It will appeal to any scholar of literature and gender working in Renaissance and seventeenth century studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aWomenxBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aWomenxBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aScotland.  aclassical authors.  aclassical inheritance.  acompetitions.  aearly modern women.  afemale friendships.  aliterary production.  apoem.  areligious sonnet sequence.  asecular sonnet sequence.1 aCottegnies, Line, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEzell, Margaret J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHackett, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaleit, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r